---
title: Crispy Chicken & Mashed Potato Bowls with Gravy, Charred Corn & Cheddar
description: Any meal that has a bowl of decadent mashed potatoes as its base has got to be good. You’ll smother the creamy spuds with a velvety homemade gravy and a generous sprinkle of cheddar before nestling a crispy, panko coated chicken cutlet on top. Buttery charred sweet corn completes this homestyle bowl of comfort.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/65f0c28ef15f35246a8cb5b4-358ba75b.jpeg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/65f0c28ef15f35246a8cb5b4.pdf
author: Michelle Doll Olson
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/crispy-chicken-and-mashed-potato-bowls-65f0c28ef15f35246a8cb5b4
servings: 2
time required: 45 minutes
cuisine: North America
nutrition:
  calories: 1000 kcal
  fat: 58 g
  saturated fat: 26 g
  carbohydrates: 69 g
  sugar: 15 g
  protein: 47 g
  fiber: 6 g
  sodium: 560 mg
course: main course
---

Wash and dry produce.

Dice @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces. Place in a #medium pot{} with enough salted water to cover by 2 inches. Bring to a boil and cook until tender, ~{10-12%minutes}. Reserve ¼ cup potato cooking liquid, then drain. Return potatoes to #pot and keep covered until ready to mash in Step 5.

Drain @corn{1}, then pat dry with paper towels. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{2%clove}.

In a #large bowl{}, whisk together one packet of @sour cream{3%tablespoon} and 2 TBSP water.

Place @panko breadcrumbs{½%cup} in #shallow dish{}; season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

Pat @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} dry with paper towels; slice lengthwise into 1-inch-thick strips (we got 3-4 strips per chicken cutlet). Season all over with @fry seasoning{1%tablespoon}, salt, and pepper.

Melt 1 TBSP @butter{4%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add corn; season with salt and pepper.

Cook, stirring occasionally, until golden brown and lightly charred in spots, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{} and cover with foil to keep warm. Wipe out pan and let cool slightly.

Melt 1 TBSP butter in pan used for corn over medium heat. Add garlic and sprinkle with @flour{1%tablespoon}; stir to combine. Whisk in @chicken stock concentrate{1} and ½ cup water.

Bring to a simmer and cook until thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Turn off heat; transfer gravy to a #small bowl{} and cover with foil to keep warm. Wash and dry pan.

> TIP: Short on time? Use a second pan for the gravy while the corn cooks!

To pot with potatoes, add remaining sour cream and 2 TBSP butter; mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth, adding splashes of reserved potato cooking liquid as needed. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Heat a ½-inch layer of @cooking oil{for frying} in pan used for gravy over medium-high heat.

Meanwhile, add chicken to #bowl{} with sour cream mixture; turn to evenly coat. Working one piece at a time, press chicken into seasoned panko until fully coated.

> TIP: For less mess, use tongs to dip and transfer.

Once oil is hot enough that a pinch of flour sizzles when added to the pan, add chicken and cook until golden brown and cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

> TIP: Fry in batches if necessary; lower heat if chicken begins to brown too quickly.

Transfer chicken to a paper-towel-lined plate.

Divide chicken, corn, and mashed potatoes between shallow #bowls{} in separate sections.

Top mashed potatoes with gravy and @cheddar cheese{½%cup}. Serve.

> TIP: If gravy is too thick, stir in 1 TBSP hot water before serving.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.